{"ts":"2026-06-26T08:24:28.523Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Accessibility Elements**\n\nOkay, I'm diving into the accessibility of CommandCenter's core components. I'm starting with `Header.tsx` and immediately found an issue: the `SOLUTIONS` nav item's dropdown button lacks `aria-haspopup` and `aria-expanded` attributes. I need to figure out the open state since it's using hover instead of click.\n\n\n**Addressing Keyboard Navigation**\n\nI've zeroed in on the desktop header and the `SOLUTIONS` dropdown. Critically, keyboard users can't trigger the dropdown because it relies solely on `group-hover`. The button doesn't toggle a state, and focus doesn't trigger anything. I'm also seeing no visible focus outline on the buttons and links, violating WCAG. I'm adding `focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-` to correct this.\n\n\n**Refining Navigation Logic**\n\nI'm now refining the navigation logic for the SOLUTIONS dropdown. I've successfully implemented `group-focus-within:flex` in Tailwind, ensuring the dropdown stays open when any contained link receives focus. This eliminates the reliance on hover alone. I've confirmed that the combination of `group-hover:flex` and `group-focus-within:flex` works beautifully, providing a robust and accessible solution. I'm also preparing to add the `aria-expanded` attribute to the button element.\n\n\n**Enhancing State Management**\n\nI'm now implementing click/hover/focus state toggling for the \"SOLUTIONS\" button. I'm adding `aria-expanded` and `aria-haspopup` attributes for proper accessibility, ensuring the dropdown responds correctly to user interactions. I'm also adding focus indicators to every link/button in `Header.tsx`. After that, I'm checking keyboard navigation for the `CommandCenter.tsx` buttons.\n\n\n"}}
